&lt;p&gt;Despite the growing body of literature on sustainable development in the healthcare fields, there is much to learn about processes and mechanisms to build a greener healthcare system and the technological, managerial, economic, and strategic impacts of net-zero policies on healthcare in the foreseen post-pandemic era. This requires engagement with questions that examine different stakeholders of the healthcare system (e.g., the policymakers, healthcare professionals, pharmaceutical companies, and patients). Thus, the aim of this special issue is to encourage scholars toward research on different promising paths to advance our understanding in building greener healthcare with the goals of net-zero carbon.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dr. Yichuan Wang&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sheffield University Management School, University of Sheffield, Conduit Rd, Sheffield S10 1FL, UK&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Email: yichuan.wang@sheffield.ac.uk&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dr. Minhao Zhang&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;School of Management, University of Bristol, Beacon House, Queens Road, Bristol, BS8 1QU, UK&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Email: minhao.zhang@bristol.ac.uk&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Prof. Benny Tjahjono&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Centre for Business in Society, Coventry University, Priory Street, Coventry, CV1 5FB, UK&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Email: benny.tjahjono@coventry.ac.uk&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the wake of the global pandemic, individuals, healthcare providers, and governments have faced several daunting challenges such as exponential growth in medical waste and carbon emissions. To address these challenges, the Pan-European Commission on Health and Sustainable Development (2021) has developed a new Call to Action on making healthcare greener in the post-pandemic era. The commissioners emphasize the need for coordinated efforts to attenuate biodiversity- and climate-related risks and call for innovative solutions to achieve sustainable healthcare. Similarly, the COP26 UN climate conference has also called for climate-resilient and low-carbon health systems to respond to mounting evidence that climate change is affecting global citizens’ health and wellbeing. To respond to these calls, the purpose of this special issue is to advance the knowledge of sustainable healthcare by encouraging research to look for innovative solutions that help achieve net-zero goals in healthcare.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Modern healthcare is one of the major contributors to pollution that adversely affects human health (Sherman et al., 2019). The global healthcare system has generated around 5% of global greenhouse gas emissions that are equivalent to the emission from 514 coal power plants (Healthcare Without Harm, 2019). Although the Paris Agreement encourages efforts to decarbonize healthcare, reducing carbon footprint through government policies and regulations, and technological innovations only indirectly affect the health sector (Bhopal &amp; Norheim, 2021). To address the growing concerns over the environmental sustainability of healthcare, researchers in the fields of cleaner production and sustainability have been putting tremendous effort into building a greener healthcare system from an individual (e.g., Xu et al., 2021), to organizational (e.g., Ryan-Fogarty et al., 2016), to industrial levels (e.g., Zimmer and McKinley, 2008).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Governmental authorities and non-governmental organizations (NGOs) have also established the decarbonization roadmaps in the healthcare sector. For example, in the UK, the national healthcare service (NHS) had committed to becoming “carbon net-zero” and already cut its own carbon footprint in 2020 by 62% compared to the international-standard 1990 baseline and by 26% when indirect factors are included. In particular, NHS addresses hospital food and catering waste, which accounts for 6% of the NHS's total greenhouse gases, by offering patients plant-based food options, implementing carbon labeling on food items, and switching to local food suppliers to reduce food miles. (NHS, 2020). Globally, with the Race-to-Zero campaign launched by the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC), more than 28,000 hospitals from 40 countries have committed to addressing health care climate challenges by 2021. This campaign targets net-zero carbon emissions by focusing on mitigation (reducing carbon footprints), resilience (preparing for extreme weather events and diseases), and leadership (providing education to promote climate change policies).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interestingly, the pandemic is bringing some positive influence on climate action. The shortage of protective equipment in the healthcare system forced the hospitals and individuals to be ‘lean’ in managing their medical resources. For instance, online medical appointments are estimated to save 40,000 cars worth of carbon annually in the UK as they become more prevalent (Patel, 2021). Meanwhile, NHS Digital creates a more efficient data hosting environment, which results in a carbon reduction of 4,000 tonnes (Patel, 2021). Thus, a growing number of healthcare organizations are implementing low-carbon, digitally-enabled healthcare services in an effort to reduce travel to healthcare facilities. Future research can explore the ways in which digital technologies can be deployed to achieve sustainable and low carbon healthcare, as well as the conditions under which a net-zero healthcare transition is feasible and desirable.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Moreover, medical waste, regarded as the second most hazardous waste globally after radiation waste, has been increased greatly due to a large number of hospitalizations and medical testing during the pandemic (Saadat et al., 2020). The pandemic has caused a significant increase in disposable personal protective equipment (PPE) such as face masks, plastic gloves and insulation garments. According to recent reports, more than 129 million disposable masks and 65 billion gloves were used globally each month (Chen et al., 2021; Prata et al., 2020). This results in a dramatic explosion of medical waste generation all over the world. However, among healthcare professionals single-use plastic is viewed as a legitimate way to prevent infectious diseases, especially single-use protective equipment is viewed as the safter option (Ngo, 2020; Xu et al., 2021). Indeed, healthcare organizations are struggling to strike a balance between achieving patient safety and long-term sustainability. Therefore, it is imperative that we find innovative solutions to this dilemma to ensure a sustainable management of medical waste (Tirkolaee et al., 2021).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Despite the growing body of literature on sustainable development in the healthcare fields, there is much to learn about processes and mechanisms to build a greener healthcare system and the technological, managerial, economic, and strategic impacts of net-zero policies on healthcare in the foreseen post-pandemic era. This requires engagement with questions that examine different stakeholders of the healthcare system (e.g., the policymakers, healthcare professionals, pharmaceutical companies, and patients). The guest editors of this special issue thus encourage scholars toward research on different promising paths to advance our understanding in building greener healthcare with the goals of net-zero carbon. We look for submissions from multiple disciplines including medicine, environmental management, sustainable marketing, engineering, operation management, information technology, psychology, and sociology. All approaches (empirical, analytical, or conceptual) that create new insights are welcome.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Topics of interest&lt;/strong&gt; include but are not limited to the following:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Resource use as input towards green healthcare systems&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Development of new systematically net-zero carbon measures for treatment pathways&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Promotion of social transition practices for reducing environmental- and climate change-related risks in healthcare&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Development of digital innovation and transformation solutions for medical waste management system in order to support healthcare provider efficiency and reduce waste&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Development of low carbon digitally enabled healthcare services and care models&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Approaches of marketing communication on social media for promoting net-zero carbon campaigns in healthcare&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Exploration of responsible and inclusive pathways to net-zero healthcare with the aid of new digital technologies such as AI and big data analytics or new carbon-free medical technologies such as battery-free EEG system&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Consumers’ and healthcare professionals’ willingness to embrace the novel greener healthcare solutions in the post-pandemic era&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Evaluation of technological, managerial, economic, and strategic impacts of net-zero policies at the individual, organizational, and industrial levels&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Net-zero initiatives and innovative business models in healthcare that reduce carbon emission&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The design of supply chain network to achieve net-zero in healthcare&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Innovative methods of measuring carbon performance in the context of healthcare&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Organizational and inter-organizational factors that drive or hinder the implementation of net-zero practices in healthcare&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Strategies and tactics for small and medium sized healthcare service businesses to achieve net-zero in considering unique operational challenges&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The role and contribution of efficient governance to the achievement of net-zero in healthcare&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Risk management for a net-zero healthcare supply chain&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Optimal utilization of Climate Investment Funds (CIF) for developing counties to accelerate climate action in healthcare&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This Special Issue is part of a collaborative special issue on “&lt;u&gt;VSI: Greener Healthcare&lt;/u&gt;” in conjunction with &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/jclepro/default1.aspx"&gt;Journal of Cleaner Production&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/CLRC/default.aspx"&gt;Cleaner Responsible Consumption&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;. The diverse scopes of these participating journals will lead to a fascinating collection of papers for readers and high visibility for authors together, to explore the multifaceted and transdisciplinary nature of this essential topic. Each paper is reviewed and accepted as fast as possible, then it will be published quickly online to be available publicly. We will then put all the published papers into a virtual special issue (VSI) and ushered by an introductory written by the Guest Editors. We will offer global promotions on multiple platforms to the selected high-quality review and research papers. For any queries, contributors with proposals for papers are encouraged to communicate with this VSI guest editors by e-mail.&lt;/p&gt;
