&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Biographies&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. Rodrigo Rabetino&lt;/strong&gt; is a Professor of Strategic Management in the School of Management and the Vaasa Energy Business Innovation Centre (VEBIC) at the University of Vaasa. His current research activities concern servitization and product-service systems, business models, and strategy as practice. He has published articles in international journals such as Regional Studies, International Journal of Management Reviews, International Journal of Operations and Production Management, Industrial Marketing Management, International Journal of Production Economics, Technovation, and Journal of Small Business Management. Moreover, Dr. Rabetino has served as guest editor in many outlets, such as Industrial Marketing Management, International Journal of Operations and Production Management, International Journal of Management Reviews, and Small Business Economics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Marko Kohtamäki&lt;/strong&gt; is a Strategy Professor and the director of the “Strategic Business Development” (SBD) research group at the University of Vaasa, a Visiting Professor at the Luleå University of Technology and the University of South-Eastern Norway, and a Docent at the University of Oulu. Prof. Kohtamäki takes particular interest in digital servitization, product-service-software innovation, organizational change, strategic practices, business intelligence, and strategic alliances. Prof. Kohtamäki has published in Strategic Management Journal, International Journal of Operations and Production Management, Strategic Entrepreneurship Journal, International Journal of Management Reviews, International Journal of Production Economics, Long Range Planning, Technovation, Industrial Marketing Management, and Journal of Business Research, amongst others.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vinit Parida&lt;/strong&gt; (Ph.D.) is a professor of entrepreneurship and innovation at Luleå University of Technology, Sweden. His research interests include servitization, product-service systems, business models, open innovation, and organizational capabilities. He has published more than 120 journal articles, including articles in Strategic Management Journal, Journal of Management Studies, Long Range Planning, Industrial Marketing Management, MIT Sloan Management Review, California Management Review, Business Strategy, and the Environment, Production and Operations Management, Journal of Cleaner Production, and others.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ferran Vendrell-Herrero&lt;/strong&gt; is an associate professor in International Business at the University of Edinburgh business school, UK. Ferran’s research aims to uncover manufacturing and creative industries innovation, digitization, and internationalization dynamics. Across these themes, he has made a distinctive contribution through publications in top academic journals, including the Journal of International Business Studies, Journal of World Business, International Journal of Production Economics, Technovation, Industrial Marketing Management, and International Business Review, among others.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At the turn of the millennium, the concept of product-service systems (PSS) evolved from the idea of integrating products and services to meet customer needs (Goedkoop et al., 1999) to the recognition that, when compared to traditional offerings, PSS are sustainable solutions that create environmental, societal, and economic value (Mont, 2002; Roy, 2000; Tukker and Tischner, 2006; Vezzoli et al., 2015). Notably, the positive impact is evident when PSS are linked to dematerialized models (Dobers and Wolff, 1999) based on selling functionality (Alonso-Rasgado et al., 2004). Thus, the notion of sustainable PSS (SPSS) (Roy, 2000) echoed a move in sustainability-related research. Academics have embraced a multidisciplinary lens to stress the importance of SPSS design-related processes and practices (Vezzoli et al., 2015), SPSS assessment (Chou et al., 2015), and SPSS implementation and business model innovation (Reim et al., 2017). Moreover, the idea of PSS turned into a suitable approach for rethinking the role of services (Manzini et al., 2001) as a means towards cleaner industrialization (Annarelli et al., 2016; Ceschin, 2013; Sousa and Cauchick Miguel, 2015).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The servitization literature has used alternative labels when referring to PSS, such as integrated solutions, advanced services, and performance- or outcome-based contracts (Rabetino et al., 2018). Although it was somehow rooted in the PSS literature and has acknowledged some relevant aspects such as the concept of life-cycle services (Rabetino et al., 2015) and alternative routes to sustainable offerings in many sectors (Naor et al., 2018; Pelli and Lähtinen, 2020), the focus on the sustainable dimension of PSS had decreased when servitization scholars borrowed the concept from technical disciplines. Accordingly, whereas Rabetino et al. (2021) found that understanding capabilities for after-sale life-cycle services was a ‘cooling topic’, Haase et al. (2017) found that many of the 52 definitions of PSS they analyzed do not refer to the environmental impact of PSS and the presence of these references have decreased over time, which represents a refocus from ecological to economic benefits (Kjaer et al., 2019).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Consequently, the time seems to have come when the servitization community could (and should) discuss the link between servitization and sustainability (Abdelkafi et al., 2022) to understand how servitization research can address and respond to the trends afflicting the planet and look for broader societal impact. Indeed, there are multiple opportunities to extend servitization research in this direction (Reim et al., 2015). For instance, in the past recent years, the Circular Economy (CE) paradigm has gained consideration as an avenue to support sustainability, while the implementation of SPSS has been pointed out as a strategy to enhance businesses circularity (Bocken et al., 2017; da Costa Fernandes et al., 2020). Although PSS do not necessarily lead to higher circularity (Kjaer et al., 2019; Pieroni et al., 2019; Tukker, 2015; Zink and Geyer, 2017) because the implementation is often product-centric (Matschewsky, 2019) and driven by profitmaking (Kjaer et al., 2019), and there exist different rebound effects (da Costa Fernandes et al., 2020), Kühl et al., (2018) suggest that offering PSS based of selling functionality incentivize manufacturers to include CE elements in their operations and, consequently, the CE framework may be an approach to analyze and overcome the impediments companies face when implementing SPSS (Hernandez, 2019) and servitization related circularity (Spring and Araujo, 2017).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Service innovation and quality (Balouei Jamkhaneh et al., 2022; Hussein Ali et al., 2022) and servitization may offer a solid basis for decarbonization towards net-zero emissions by combining business and technical approaches. Notwithstanding some remarkable exceptions (Bressanelli et al., 2018a, 2018b; Coreynen et al., 2021; Marić and Opazo-Basáez, 2019; Opazo-Basáez et al., 2018), the full benefits of sustainability- and circularity-oriented servitization are not entirely studied. Moreover, although there has been a proliferation of publications on the link between PSS and CE over the past five years (da Costa Fernandes et al., 2020; Kjaer et al., 2019; Kühl et al., 2019), there is no commonly agreed meaning of a ‘circular product-service system’ or a complete understanding of how the use of PSS contributes to circularity (Blomsma et al., 2018; da Costa Fernandes et al., 2020; Matschewsky, 2019). Undoubtedly, these opportunities are more significant and their exploration more exciting when we consider the convergence between the twin transitions of servitization and digitalization (Bressanelli et al., 2018a, 2018b), resulting in the trend known as digital servitization (Kohtamäki et al., 2019).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Indeed, we do not talk about a twin transition, but rather we speak of a triplet transition, including digitization, servitization, and the sustainable transition; being the focus on understanding and advancing support practices and business models when transforming business operations while considering the triplet transition’s three dimensions and the interplay at the ecosystem level (Yin et al., 2020). In other words, digital servitization allows companies to deliver product-service-software systems that are still typically driven by profitability and cost-effectiveness but do not fully consider sustainability-and circularity-related aspects.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Topic areas of interest&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Against the above backdrop, this Special Issue call invites multidisciplinary conceptual and empirical contributions concerning (digital) servitization in supporting sustainability, circularity, green/sustainable supply chain, and resource wisdom in manufacturing. The SI aims to discuss the interplay between institutional influences, ecosystem dynamics, and strategic and innovation practices. We are particularly interested in business model innovation towards sustainable digital servitization and studies on achieving sustainability and circularity through PSS and sustainable life-cycle service offerings. Thus, we want to encourage scholars to submit research contributions based on established knowledge in servitization and PSS. We seek submissions from various perspectives with original and advanced thinking on sustainable and circular servitization. The overarching question is, how does embedding sustainability into business models through (digital) servitization strategies call for new organizational and ecosystem-wide practices that enable value creation and capture in manufacturing? We welcome academically-oriented papers with solid conceptual grounding that should look for, but not be limited to, answers to the following preliminary questions:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How does digitization enable sustainability-oriented business model innovation, novel value creation, and capture practices in servitizing companies?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can digital servitization contribute to sustainability and sustainable value chain management?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How could revenue streams from digitally-enabled services support sustainable practices in SME companies and their customers?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How does digitization influence servitization strategies? And how do the resulting servitized business models support sustainable practices?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Review process&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
