&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Introduction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Digitalization and information technologies are shaping novel societies, bringing different technological developments in field of engineering (Nižetić et al., 2020), ensuring various potential benefits for society in the future terms. On the other side, each technological development has got its price and where sustainability aspect becomes critical. The use of limited raw materials needs to be considered as well as also unknown impacts of information technologies on the environment, (Zhang et al., 2022). Energy field become dynamic and mainly driven by ongoing energy transition (Arora et al., 2022) that requires increase in renewable energy capacities (Saba et al., 2022), followed by energy efficiency (Adly et al., 2022), and finally more advanced energy storage solutions (Zarate-Perez et al., 2022). The impact of digitalization in the energy field is complex ones since focus can be directed on various aspects. For instance, digitalization in the energy generation systems ensures higher overall efficiency of the generation systems followed by better flexibility in various operating circumstances. Moreover, transmission and grid systems can also have benefits by involvement of smart information technologies that would ensure more advanced energy interconnectivity, communication and energy balancing between different energy systems. The final energy users, i.e. energy dissipations systems can be also better controlled and operated by involvement of information technologies. From, previous aspect, digitalization can also secure efficient communication, integration and finally balancing between production, transmission and consumption side.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The role of digitalization is rapidly progressing in several major fields that are important to the population such as; circular economy (Fan et al., 2020), waste management and elimination (Goutam Mukherjee et al., 2021), renewable energy concepts (Boddapati et al., 2022), energy storage technologies (Gupta et al., 2022), e-health (Rayan et al., 2022), followed by other areas where digitalization is bringing advancements. No matter that benefits of digitalization are already visible through interesting technological solutions, the key and important aspect must be directed to analysis and tracking of different environmental footprints, in order to minimize their impact. Therefore, the environmental protection is area of interest where digitalization can also help to reduce and to minimize harmful impacts of smart technologies on environment, especially in cities or high dense populated areas, (Balova et al., 2021).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Various engineering disciplines are called upon to provide their input, ensure the diffusion of fundamental and applied knowledge. The final goal is to secure knowledge towards firm actions that would help to solve the present and upcoming challenges of the population.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The virtual Special Volume (VSI) will include invited extended papers from &lt;strong&gt;SpliTech2022&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;strong&gt;7&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; International Conference on Smart and Sustainable Technologies&lt;/strong&gt;), that was held on hybrid way from July 5&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; to 8&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; in Bol (Island of Brač) and Split, Croatia. The SpliTech conference is a multidisciplinary conference covering a range of topics, but with a focus on smart and sustainable technologies towards a smart and low-carbon development. The participants at the &lt;strong&gt;SpliTech2022&lt;/strong&gt; are highly encouraged to submit papers to this Special Volume for possible publication in JCLP. Authors who have not attended the conference but have suitable papers in hands are also welcome to submit a paper for this virtual Special Volume.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This SV is open to all engineering disciplines and a wide range of research topics addressing smart and sustainable technologies in general with focus on the digitalization in field of energy and sustainability, i.e. cleaner aspect should be demonstrated and discussed. The main emphasis would be directed to the core digitalization benefits and on the other side, how to reduce potential harmful impacts to the environment as unavoidable side effect of ongoing digitalization. Review papers are also accepted with the main focus being on advancements in digitalization with a strong link to practical applications in all sectors, however with emphasis on Energy sector as key one.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Journal of Cleaner Production is a well-known and important platform for sharing multidisciplinary knowledge, innovations directed to cleaner production and sustainable development. Therefore, this VSI encourages submission of cross-disciplinary research work addressing major contemporary issues and exploring solutions to build a sustainable future.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. Topical areas&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This “Call for Papers” (CfPs) for the VSI of the Journal of Cleaner Production (JCLP) provides opportunities for scholars, industrial researchers, business and governmental officers to collaborate and accelerate the transition towards a smart and sustainable society. Papers should include comprehensive, up-to-date literature reviews, combined with novel theoretical and experimental investigations.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Potential topics for this VSI include, but will not be limited to, the following key topical areas:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(1) Digitalization in energy systems, processes and technologies&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(2) Digitalization in circular economy and waste management&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(3) Digitalization in environmental protection&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(4) Digitalization in smart city concept&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The energy systems are shifting to towards renewable energy sources with gradual reduction of the fossil based generation technologies as part of the ongoing energy transition. The role of digitalization in energy generation systems is to improve their operation, economic suitability and as well as to minimize an impact of the specific generation technologies to the environment. The more efficient control, demand side management and flexibility to the stochastic operating conditions would lead to the energy efficiency improvement of the generation systems. Demonstration and application of the novel smart solutions in the energy generation systems is necessary with respect to the energy transition.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The circular economy aspect is critical one since there are ongoing global and demanding problems regarding the waste issue. Significant waste generation (plastic waste, electronic waste, food waste, etc.) is creating severe issues to the environment, while on the other side in some economic branches there would be lack of raw resources in the close future. There is obvious need for further development of existing circular economy concepts and to maximize use of waste as the useful raw source for further processing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The environmental protection approaches can be also upgraded by implementation of digitalization technologies. The main goal is to develop smart and advanced monitoring and alerting systems in order to prevent harmful potential conditions in specific areas.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Finally, the&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;Smart city concept is very dynamic and promising research field as it demonstrates possible and effective integration of digitalization, with respect to the typical infrastructure demands, i.e. requests in the nowadays dense and populated cities or urban areas. The improvements of the cities infrastructure, security and life quality are significant ones and that can be achieved by proper application of the smart products and technologies. The benefits of the digitalization within the smart city concept are significant ones, however, the more intense research activity is needed in this area in order to better understand the limits and general capabilities of digitalization.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Contributors with proposals for papers are encouraged to communicate with the Co-editors by e-mail. The following schedule will guide the development of this VSI:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;September 1, 2022:&lt;/strong&gt; Publication of the CfPs for this VSIOctober 1, 2022 to March 1, 2023: Submission of full papers (‘peer-review ready’) via the EM system. Please select the Article Type: ‘&lt;strong&gt;SpliTech2022&lt;/strong&gt;’ when submitting your document to Elsevier for the peer review process.March 2023 to August 2023: Peer review process – Provide feedback to authors+Submission of revised papers+ Second round of reviews finished.&lt;br&gt;September 2023: Final publication of the VSI&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Full papers are invited for potential publication in this VSI of the &lt;em&gt;Journal of Cleaner Production &lt;/em&gt;&amp; &lt;em&gt;Cleaner Energy Systems&lt;/em&gt;. Submissions should be between 9,000 and 13,000 words for comprehensive/integrative reviews, between 7,000 and 8,500 words for &lt;strong&gt;full research/theoretical papers&lt;/strong&gt; with broad empirical studies, and between 5,000 and 7,000 words for &lt;strong&gt;case studies.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All authors with accepted abstracts must follow &lt;em&gt;Journal of Cleaner Production &lt;/em&gt;“Guide for Authors” which can be accessed via the following link: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/journals/journal-of-cleaner-production/0959-6526/guide-for-authors"&gt;Guide for authors - Journal of Cleaner Production - ISSN 0959-6526 (elsevier.com)&lt;/a&gt; and follow the standard submission procedures of Elsevier’s Editorial System (EES). To submit a manuscript, please go to &lt;a href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/jclepro/default2.aspx"&gt;Editorial Manager®&lt;/a&gt; and select this virtual Special Volume “&lt;strong&gt;SpliTech2022&lt;/strong&gt;”. All submissions are subject to standard peer review, revision, and re-submission processes. The manuscripts may be rejected after these processes due to poor quality.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Papers must be written in good English. Authors with limitations in the command of written English are recommended to have their papers edited by an &lt;strong&gt;English Sciencitific Editor&lt;/strong&gt; before the first submission because poorly written pieces can compromise the decisions during the review process. Similarly, they should have their final document edited by an &lt;strong&gt;English Sciencitific Editor&lt;/strong&gt; before they submit it to the editorial team for the final review and for publication within the Journal of Cleaner Production.&lt;/p&gt;
