&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the fast-changing current global business environment, sustainability and circularity in supply chains have become a recognized field of investigation across multiple operations research disciplines. Circular supply chains are critical for maximizing value creation throughout a product's life cycle (Mogale et al., 2022). Companies can spend less on raw materials with a circular supply chain, reducing the risk of price volatility (Nag et al., 2021). Therefore, many companies opt to collect their end-of-life (EOL) products to disassemble and return them to their raw material form to deal with growing raw material costs and volatile availability. Additionally, with the rise of shorter product lifecycles, supply chains must address greater amounts of obsolete and EOL products. However, the success of closing the loop in supply chains is largely dependent on the participation of consumers (Najmi et al., 2022). As a result, the parties' roles are reversed in this case, with the customer acting as the product's supplier (Bouzon et al., 2018; Mina et al., 2021).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Consumers, as suppliers in reverse supply chain contexts, are often unaware of the environmental harm that solid waste poses (i.e., e-waste). Consumers must make items available to manufacturers so that they have a proper final destination, while manufacturers must provide consumers with many options to encourage them to return the products (Kerber et al., 2021). Thus, the willingness of consumers to return their used products is critical to reverse supply chain success. A few people embrace the proactive approach and perform social responsibility by returning unwanted goods to collection centers. In this sense, consumers should be rewarded for returning their used goods (Mogali et al., 2022).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Even considering the crucial role of consumers in closing the supply chain, the literature on circular supply chains is primarily focused on B2B situations. Exploring the consumer side of the product, the starting point of the product in such a situation, is still very limited (Najmi et al., 2022). Moreover, the majority of previous research has focused solely on recycling, with few studies discussing other options for EOL products such as returning and disposing or donating and reselling. Previous research has ignored uncertain markets, conditions of returned products, and incentives (Mogali et al., 2022). Moreover, besides EOL returns, it is crucial to consider the rise of e-commerce and omnichannel in the past years, areas that particularly increased by the COVID-19 pandemic. E-commerce is undoubtedly the most visible and well-known force shaping today's supply chains (Jena &amp; Meena, 2022). With this growth, the number of products returned by consumers to retailers has achieved the mark of US $428 billion in 2020 (National Retail Federation, 2021).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Furthermore, consumers have a special part in the operationalization of Extended Producer Responsibility (EPR) (Koshta et al., 2022; Islam et al., 2021). The discovery of factors that influence consumer return behavior is required to increase customer engagement, especially in e-waste collecting schemes. In this sense, technologies from Industry 4.0 may assist companies to better design and operate reverse networks to enhance product return. Through simulation tools and automated manufacturing lines, technologies from Industry 4.0 may assist current circular economy (CE) initiatives. The use of tools like digital platforms, blockchain, data science, machine learning, and artificial intelligence (AI) can support decision-making along product end-of-life. In this context, machine learning and AI are notably crucial to fostering the integration of people, processes, and systems in a wide range of operational situations along circular supply chains.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In conclusion, there is a gap with regard to the trending shift towards exploring the consumer side of the EOL product return. Managing a successful circular supply chain will require initiatives that also consider user experience, customer centricity, and customer loyalty, in addition to investigations on barriers and drivers for closing the loop from the consumer perspective. With these concerns in mind, the guiding research question of this call for papers is: “What are the challenges and opportunities to better involve, motivate, and engage the consumer in closing the loop of supply chain towards circular systems?”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The objective of this CFP is to unveil practices, initiatives, tools, structures, and aspects related to closing the supply chain loop by considering consumer centricity as a supplier in the reverse cycle. This new picture reinforces the need to uncover these aspects regarding product return behavior to achieve sustainable goals.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Considering this proposed topic of this Call for Papers, the guest editors of the SI of the JCLP and CLSCN entitled “&lt;em&gt;Consumer role in product end-of-life return: challenges and opportunities for circular supply chains&lt;/em&gt;” welcome analytical, empirical, conceptual, quantitative, and qualitative research studies. Dealing with the aforementioned scenarios will enable the development of key trends for the future, and respecting the high academic standards expected for JCLP and CLSC journal, this Call for Papers is focused upon but &lt;u&gt;not limited&lt;/u&gt; to the subsequent themes:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Promising digital technologies, strategies, and innovative solutions to motivate EOL product return;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Analysis of barriers and drivers for EOL product return from consumers’ perspectives;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Reverse supply chain integration, collaboration, big data, and digitalization towards enhancing EOL product return;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Product return in e-commerce and omnichannel operations;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use of predictive and prescriptive analytics (big data and algorithms) for greater visibility, predictability, and data-driven decision-making in product return;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;New business models and digital platforms that foster collaboration throughout the circular supply chain;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Supply Chain Network Design (SCND) considering consumer willingness to return products;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Application of IoT technologies for product use traceability;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Hypotheses testing regarding consumer behavior for returning products;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The role and mechanisms of manufacturers in transforming consumer intention into behavior to return products;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Remote monitoring for manufacturing, product usage, remanufacturing and recycling;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Engineering and design of circular products, processes and/or supply chains as solutions to climate changes;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Studies based on theories regarding consumer behavior (theory of planned behavior, consumer behavior theory, etc.) to uncover the effects of proper infrastructure, incentive schemes, collection boxes, proximity, and convenience on EOL product return.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
