&lt;p&gt;There are urgent needs to make supply chains more resilient to support societal transitions to equitable, sustainable, post-fossil carbon societies, which are based upon circular economies. Authors are invited to address issues related to supply chains that increasingly integrate climate-change related risks that are driven by the annual 81 million increase in the human population that continue to increase food insecurity and the probability of more severe and frequent storms as well as increase the probability of COVID-19-like pandemics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All of these interconnected dimensions make it increasingly important that improvements in forward and reverse supply chains, are made so they are less vulnerable to disruptions locally, regionally, nationally and globally. Our editorial team, looks forward to receiving your creative, challenging and future-oriented contributions for this special issue.&lt;/p&gt;
