&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This special issue is a collaborative-special issue between the &lt;em&gt;Journal of Cleaner Production and the Journal of Cleaner Logistics and Supply Chains&lt;/em&gt;, which will contribute to a high-visibility collection of quality articles on diverse topics related to sustainable supply chains. We welcome articles that address any of the following themes: (Note: We will also welcome articles that address issues that may not fit into any of these themes.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Effective and efficient supply and demand planning;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Improved, holistic supply chain risk management; frameworks, processes and policies;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Demand, supply and information risks and how to more effectively manage the complex supply networks;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Integrated business planning solutions that can anticipate and solve complex supply chain challenges;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Enterprise resource planning concepts, tools, procedures, policies and solutions;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Data science and AI/Machine learning methods and the inter-related requirements towards mitigating the negative impacts of climate changes, pandemics, wars and other challenges that may rupture supply chains and the inter-dependent product-service systems;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Engineering and design of sustainable products, processes and/or supply chains as solutions to climate changes;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Human/Machine interaction issues and a framework to solve the new generation work force planning problems such as the need for lifelong learning opportunities, unemployment and worker disillusionment;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Remote monitoring for manufacturing, product usage, remanufacturing and recycling;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Reverse flow planning and remanufacturing in the medical industry including products, accessories and equipment;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Forward and reverse supply chain planning and their increased relevance in post-covid, equitable and sustainable societies.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are invited to submit your manuscript at any time before the submission deadline. For any inquiries about the appropriateness of contribution topics, please contact &lt;strong&gt;Dr. Subramoniam&lt;/strong&gt; via &lt;a href="mailto:Ramesh.Subramoniam@utdallas.edu"&gt;Ramesh.Subramoniam@utdallas.edu&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The journal's submission platform (&lt;a href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/clscn/default1.aspx"&gt;EditorialManager&lt;sup&gt;®&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/a&gt;) is now available for receiving submissions to this Special Issue. Please refer to the Guide for Authors to prepare your manuscript, and select the article type of “&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;VSI:SUSTAINABLE SUPPLY CHAIN&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;” when submitting your manuscript online. &lt;strong&gt;The submission deadline is 31 July 2023.&lt;/strong&gt; Both the Guide for Authors and the submission portal could be found on the Journal Homepage here: &lt;a href="https://www.journals.elsevier.com/cleaner-logistics-and-supply-chain"&gt;Cleaner Logistics and Supply Chain - Journal - Elsevier&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All the submissions deemed suitable to be sent for peer review will be reviewed by at least two independent reviewers. Upon its editorial acceptance, your article will go into production immediately. It will be published in the latest regular issue, while be presented on the specific Special Issue webpage simultaneously.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Keywords:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sustainability, supply chain planning, risk prevention/reduction/management, digital technologies, remanufacturing, recycling, improving supply-chain resilience, mis-information risks, demand planning, stimulation of innovative transitions to sustainable, post-fossil carbon societies, cyber-security, ESG, innovative policies at corporate and governmental levels&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Why publish in this Special Issue?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Special Issue articles are published together on ScienceDirect, making it incredibly easy for other researchers to discover your work.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Special content articles are downloaded on ScienceDirect twice as often within the first 24 months than articles published in regular issues.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Special content articles attract 20% more citations in the first 24 months than articles published in regular issues.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;All articles in this special issue will be reviewed by no fewer than two independent experts to ensure the quality, originality and novelty of the work published.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Low-carbon mobility is at the heart of a new, sustainable transition of smart cities (Kley et al., 2011; Secinaro et al., 2021). Worldwide, many policy bodies are incentivizing manufacturers, vendors, and customers towards low-carbon forms of transportation (European Commission, 2021; OECD, 2014). Because of their varied, and often compact layout, researchers have identified opportunities for manufacturers of electric (EV) and hydrogen (FCEV) vehicles to create a multi-modal design paired with electric and traditional bicycles (Bigerna et al., 2016; Laurischkat et al., 2016; Graziano et all, 2020; Kazemzadeh &amp; Bansal, 2021; Gallaher et al., 2021).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, for industrial groups &amp; business choices to promote sustainable mobility actions it is crucial to discover how their business model can evolve to withstand such a fast-paced change.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For example, automotive and e-bike producers have to make strategic choices that go beyond the vehicles, and include charging technologies, driver services, eletricity management, and commercial contracts, along with new production and assembly processes (Zuev, 2019; Secinaro et al., 2020, 2022; Papacharalampopoulos et al., 2020; Graziano, 2021).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Overall, to political institutions whether a low carbon transition will be driven by electric mobility is relatively indifferent (Lieven, 2015). Institutions like the European Union (EU) or the US have made commitments on overall targets, rather than on specific paths of transition. For example, in the EU, countries have pledged to reduce greenhouse has emissions by at least 55% by 2030 compared to 1990 levels.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this context, the change of business models towards the production of electric vehicles is just around the corner and at the top of their strategic plans for the coming years.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://api.journals.elsevier.com/media/1gddkzbp/marcello-graziano.png" alt=""&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dr. Marcello Graziano&lt;br&gt;Organization: Southern Connecticut State University, Department of Management and International Business, USA&lt;br&gt;Email: grazianom5@southernct.edu&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://api.journals.elsevier.com/media/2iqd2ahd/paolo-biancone.png" alt=""&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Prof. Paolo Biancone&lt;br&gt;Organization: University of Turin, Department of Management, Italy&lt;br&gt;Email: paolo.biancone@unito.it&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This special issue aims at hosting theoretical and empirical works focusing on the changes in the mobility sector driven by a transition towards a low carbon future. Specific topics in this special issue will include (but are not limited to):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;• Sustainable production processes of the electric vehicles and motorbikes; &lt;br&gt;• Sustainable production processes of hydrogen vehicles;&lt;br&gt;• Sustainable production processes of e-bikes;&lt;br&gt;• Changes in manufacturers' business models to meet the new demand for electric mobility;&lt;br&gt;• Government policies to support the adoption of electric vehicles; &lt;br&gt;• Energy management for both electric and hydrogen;&lt;br&gt;• Charging technologies for the future of mobility; &lt;br&gt;• New driver services; &lt;br&gt;• Commercial contracts; &lt;br&gt;• Customer purchase orientation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To submit a manuscript, please firstly go to &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/journal-of-cleaner-production"&gt;Journal of Cleaner Production | ScienceDirect.com by Elsevier&lt;/a&gt; and select the Special issue “&lt;strong&gt;Disruptive mobility for smart cities&lt;/strong&gt;”. All submissions are subject to standard peer review, revision, and re-submission processes. For any queries, contributors with proposals for papers are encouraged to communicate with this VSI guest editors by e-mail.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Submission deadline: 30/09/2023&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;References:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bigerna, S., Bollino, C. A., &amp; Micheli, S. (2016). Italian youngsters' perceptions of alternative fuel vehicles: A fuzzy-set approach. Journal of Business Research, 69(11), 5426-5430.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;European Commission (2021). CO₂ emission performance standards for cars and vans (2020 onwards). https://ec.europa.eu/clima/policies/transport/vehicles/regulation_en#tab-0-0&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Gallaher, A., Graziano, M., &amp; Fiaschetti, M. (2021). Legacy and shockwaves: A spatial analysis of strengthening resilience of the power grid in Connecticut. Energy Policy, 159, 112582.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Graziano, M., Gunther, P., Carstensen, F.V., Gallaher, A., Becker, B. (2020). The wider regional benefits of power grids improved resilience through tree-trimming operations: evidences from Connecticut, USA. Energy Policy, 138, 111293. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Graziano, M. (2019), Solar power: Participation is the fuel. News &amp; Views of Nature Energy, 4: 2012-2013. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Laurischkat, K., Viertelhausen, A., &amp; Jandt, D. (2016). Business models for electric mobility. Procedia Cirp, 47, 483-488.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Lieven, T. (2015). Policy measures to promote electric mobility–A global perspective. Transportation Research Part A: Policy and Practice, 82, 78-93.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Kazemzadeh, K., &amp; Bansal, P. (2021). Electric bike navigation comfort in pedestrian crowds. Sustainable Cities and Society, 69, 102841.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Kley, F., Lerch, C., &amp; Dallinger, D. (2011). New business models for electric cars—A holistic approach. Energy policy, 39(6), 3392-3403.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Papacharalampopoulos A. and Michail C., Stavropoulos P. (2020). Manufacturing Process Control Through a Digital Twin: Encoding Issues. TESConf 2020 - 9th International Conference on Through-life Engineering Services, https://ssrn.com/abstract=3718017 or http://dx.doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.3718017&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Secinaro, S., Brescia, V., Calandra, D., &amp; Biancone, P. (2020). Employing bibliometric analysis to identify suitable business models for electric cars. Journal of Cleaner Production, 121503.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Secinaro, S., Brescia, V., Calandra, D., &amp; Biancone, P. (2021). Towards a hybrid model for the management of smart city initiatives. Cities, 116, 103278.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Secinaro, S., Calandra, D., Lanzalonga, F., &amp; Ferraris, A. (2022). Electric vehicles’ consumer behaviours: Mapping the field and providing a research agenda. Journal of Business Research, 150, 399-416.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Stavropoulos, P., Papacharalampopoulos, A., Michail, C., Vassilopoulos, V., Alexopoulos, K., &amp; Perlo, P. (2021). A two-stage decision support system for manufacturing processes integration in microfactories for electric vehicles. Procedia Manufacturing, 54, 106-111.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;OECD (2014). The Cost of Air Pollution. Health Impacts of Road Transport. https://www.oecd.org/environment/tools-evaluation/the-cost-of-air-pollution-9789264210448-en.htm&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Zuev, D., Tyfield, D., &amp; Urry, J. (2019). Where is the politics? E-bike mobility in urban China and civilizational government. Environmental Innovation and Societal Transitions, 30, 19-32.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Keywords&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(Smart cities) OR (Smart city) AND (Mobility) OR (Urban Mobility) AND (Vehicle’s Sustainable production) AND (Charging Technologies) AND (Business models) AND (Electric mobility) AND (Hydrogen Mobility)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This Special Issue intends to present key recent developments in the areas of more efficient energy use, cleaner fuels and biofuels, cleaner production, CO2 mitigation and capture, optimisation and waste management. The provided topical coverage reflects the breadth of the research presented at the conference, upgraded with follow-up research by the authors and thorough selection by the Guest Editors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prof. Dr. Panos Seferlis&lt;br&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Aristotle University of Thessaloniki&lt;br&gt;&lt;a href="mailto:seferlis@auth.gr"&gt;seferlis@auth.gr&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. Bohong Wang&lt;br&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Zhejiang Ocean University&lt;br&gt;&lt;a href="mailto:wangbh@zjou.edu.cn"&gt;wangbh@zjou.edu.cn&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The current environmental and societal sustainability issues and challenges of GHG reduction, toxic and particulates pollution, water use minimization, wastewater treatment, recycling and reuse of material and energy remain extremely complex, highly interactive and strongly interdependent. The mitigation measures and actions therefore require holistic approaches and sound methods for implementable solutions. In an extremely volatile world recovering from a shock of unprecedented proportions such as the COVID pandemic supply of resources and energy, recycle and reuse of material and energy streams, and the delivery of produced goods add to an increasingly vulnerable production system and societal integrity. Holistic approaches in the form of process integration employing rigorous and accurate in predictions models and systematic optimisation procedures enable increased process performance at the best possible efficiency level in material and energy utilisation ensuring the satisfaction of environmental and societal sustainability goals. The 25th conference “Process Integration, Modelling and Optimisation for Energy Saving and Pollution Reduction – PRES’22 that is held in Bol (Split) – Croatia, during September 5-8 2022, provides a platform for discussing ideas and developing solutions for cleaner processes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are invited to submit your manuscript at any time before the submission deadline. For any inquiries about the appropriateness of contribution topics, please contact The Managing Guest Editor Dr Petar Sabev Varbanov via Email on &lt;a href="mailto:varbanov@fme.vutbr.cz"&gt;varbanov@fme.vutbr.cz&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The journal’s submission platform (Editorial Manager®) is now available for receiving submissions to this Special Issue (URL &lt;a href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/cles/"&gt;https://www.editorialmanager.com/cles/&lt;/a&gt;). Please refer to the Guide for Authors to prepare your manuscript, and select the article type of “&lt;u&gt;VSI: PRES'22&lt;/u&gt;” when submitting your manuscript online. Both the Guide for Authors and the submission portal could be found on the Journal Homepage here: &lt;a href="https://www.journals.elsevier.com/cleaner-energy-systems"&gt;https://www.journals.elsevier.com/cleaner-energy-systems&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Keywords:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Process integration, process and societal sustainability, recycle and reuse&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Textile and apparel industry is considered as one of the world’s most polluting industries, where there are various sustainable challenges, including industrial waste, garment remnants, carbon emission and post-consumer waste. Thus it is urgent and essential to adopt a full-spectrum approach to sustainability through phasing out and substituting unsustainable manufacturing practices globally. Motivated by this consideration, this special issue calls for papers that address this critical research need, developing a body of knowledge on how a meaningful shift towards sustainability within the textile and apparel industry can be achieved.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The journal's submission platform (&lt;a href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/jclepro/default1.aspx"&gt;Editorial Manager®&lt;/a&gt;) is now available for receiving submissions to this Special Issue. Please refer to the Guide for Authors to prepare your manuscript, and select the article type of “&lt;strong&gt;VSI: Sustainable transition&lt;/strong&gt;” when submitting your manuscript online. The submission deadline is &lt;strong&gt;30 September 2023&lt;/strong&gt;. Both the Guide for Authors and the submission portal could be found on the Journal Homepage here: &lt;a href="https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-cleaner-production/"&gt;https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-cleaner-production/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
