editors.biography:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Professor Mattias Lindahl &lt;/em&gt;is among the top internationally-recognized scholars in the areas of Ecodesign and Product Service Systems (PSS). He has conducted research and teaching in EcoDesign since 1997, and research and teaching in Integrated Product Service Engineering (IPSE) also often called PSS since 1999.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Most of his PSS and EcoDesign research has been in cooperation with companies. Mattias is a project leader for several major research projects and not at least program director for Mistra REES &ndash; Resource-Efficient and Effective Solutions based on circular economy thinking (2015-2019), a 8.3MEuro program with more than 18 researchers and 14 involved companies.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He has been involved in the writing of the ISO 14006 (2001) EcoDesign standard and is currently the chairman of the Swedish committee, and the main technical expert in the development of the new IEC/ISO JWG ECD 62959 &ldquo;Environmentally Conscious Design &ndash; Principles, requirements and guidance&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt;

Professor Bing-Jie Ni received his PhD degree in environmental engineering in June 2009. He currently is an ARC Future Fellow and professor at University of Technology Sydney. He has been working in the field of environmental technology and wastewater treatment, particularly the interface among process engineering, microbial biotechnology, materials science and mathematical modeling, focusing on the integration of these disciplines to develop innovative and sustainable technological solutions to achieve high-levels of pollutant removal from wastewater with a minimised carbon emissions and maximised energy recovery, in order to transform wastes or wastewater from a troublesome pollutant to a valuable resource and save large quantities of greenhouse gas emissions. 

Professor Ni has published 2 research books, 30 book chapters, and more than 420 papers in refereed SCI journals, including over 120 papers in Nature index journals. He has won over 20 Government, University and Industry research grants with a total research funding of more than AUD 10 M over the last 10 years. He serves as Editor, Associate Editor, Guest Editor, or Editorial Board for several top journals in the field. He has delivered over 20 keynote speeches at national and international conferences, and has chaired over 10 national and international conference sessions. He is the inventor of over 10 granted patents for relevant technologies he developed, with some of them currently being commercialized for translating his research outcomes to end users. He is a Highly Cited Researcher - Clarivate Analytics - Web of Science. He has received more than 50 awards &amp; prizes since 2009, for example, he has been recognized by Engineers Australia as one of Australia&rsquo;s most innovative engineers primarily for his work on greenhouse gas neutral water management.
 &lt;a href="https://profiles.uts.edu.au/Bingjie.Ni"&gt;Editor's Personal Website&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I graduated from the Universiti Teknologi Malaysia (UTM), Faculty of Chemical and Energy Engineering, Department of Bioprocess Engineering. I pursued my Msc in Industrial Environmental Management from the University of Abertay, Dundee, UK. My research area is focusing on the valorisation of organic waste through composting and anaerobic digestion, with the use of mathematical modelling for the simulation and optimisation of the process. I am also interested in the field of waste-to-energy, biofuel, modelling, wastewater treatment, supply chain design and low carbon development. I am actively involved in some of the low carbon projects in Malaysia and is the organising committee of conferences.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Keywords: Organic waste management; Anaerobic digestion; Composting; Modelling &amp; Kinetics; GHG; Biomass &amp; Bioenergy; Low carbon; Environmental management; Wastewater; Solid waste&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

callforPapers.explain:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Please note that the Article Publishing Charge shall be waived for all article submitted towards this Special Issue.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The rapid advancement of computing technologies and big data processing techniques have facilitated the implementation of Artificial Intelligence (AI) in Education (AIED) applications and tools. In the near future, AI is expected to play an increasingly central role in the provision and education services in K-12 as well as in Higher Education contexts. New tools and services driven by AI and machine learning techniques are being deployed in chatbots, intelligent tutoring systems, automated grading systems and other algorithmic facilitated decision systems in the education sector. This Special Issue takes aim at these questions with a focus on equity, responsibility, fairness, autonomy, accountability, and transparency in the development and deployment of AIED.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prof. Milrad&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Department of Computer Science and Media Technology&lt;br&gt;Linnaeus University, Sweden&lt;br&gt;marcelo.milrad@lnu.se&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prof. Cerratto-Pargman&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Department of Computer Science&lt;br&gt;Stockholm University, Sweden&lt;br&gt;tessy@dsv.su.se&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Assoc. Prof. McGrath&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Department of Education&lt;br&gt;Stockholm University, Sweden&lt;br&gt;cormac.mcgrath@edu.su.se&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The rapid advancement of computing technologies and big data processing techniques have facilitated the implementation of Artificial Intelligence in Education (AIED) applications and tools. In the near future, AI is expected to play an increasingly central role in the provision and education services in K-12 as well as in Higher Education contexts. New tools and services driven by AI and machine learning techniques are being deployed in chatbots, intelligent tutoring systems, automated grading systems and other algorithmic facilitated decision systems in the education sector. Such AIED technologies are expected to provide personalized guidance, support, and feedback to students and assist teachers and policymakers in decision-making in a wide range of formal educational contexts (Hwang et al., 2020).&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Emerging research suggests that the use of AI in educational contexts has the potential to support teaching &amp; learning as well as improve human performance. At the same time, the misuse of AI due to algorithm bias and a lack of governance could inhibit human rights and result in solidifying existing inequalities (Prinsloo, 2020; Yang et al., 2021).&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Responsible AI relates to human responsibility for developing and deploying AIED systems that align with fundamental human principles and values to safeguard human flourishing and well-being (Dignum, 2019). Responsibility can relate to the design of systems, their deployment, and how end-users understand and adopt them. Holmes et al. (2021), for instance, identify that AIED ethics consists of three interrelated dimensions; a) ethics of data, referring to ethical concerns related to data management, b) ethics of algorithms and computational approaches in education pertaining to choices for decision-making models’ development and c) ethics of education and pedagogy addressing the implications applications of AIED may have on professional practice, but also about end-users literacy when engaging with AIED. Such multiplicity and complexity of AIED development and deployment prompt central questions about equity, responsibility, fairness, autonomy, accountability, and transparency from a more integrative view of ethical issues and moral dilemmas and ethics in practice (Prinsloo, 2020; Slade and Prinsloo, 2013, Ceratto-Pargman &amp; McGrath, 2021; Velander et al., 2021).&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The specific focus of this special issue is concerned with a range of questions as enumerated below:&lt;br&gt;• How are AIED tools, systems, and artefacts designed, developed, and deployed to align with human and educational values?&lt;br&gt;• What constitutes an equitable use of AIED systems?&lt;br&gt;• How are different ethical standpoints or guidelines considered in the design, development, and deployment of AIED, and what conflicts arise as a result, if any?&lt;br&gt;• When developing models to predict outputs and personalize learning across cohorts, how are ethics considered?&lt;br&gt;• How can AIED decisions be presented transparently and in an explainable manner enabling end-users to trust AIED systems?&lt;br&gt;• How do AIED design practices address the risks of bias?&lt;br&gt;• How are students and teachers’ AI literacy considered in designing, developing, and deploying AIED?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Research areas / Topics to be addressed:&lt;br&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;We welcome original contributions addressing conceptual aspects as well as empirical research on responsible AI issues in education. Papers submitted to this special issue should address and focus on equity, fairness, accountability, or transparency in relation to and in the context of education and associated practices. These contributions should be grounded in substantive ethical reasoning.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Contributions could include empirical studies focusing on the design of ethically sensitive AIED, where systems are conceptualized, designed, and trained to act ethically. We also welcome case studies related to the implementation of AIED tools and systems where practices have been potentially disrupted, with a focus on end-user perspectives&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Another type of scientific contribution could address empirical studies focusing on stakeholder perspectives (e.g., developers, students, faculty, management, policymakers, etc.) views on equity and responsibility. Additional possible directions may include aspects related to policy and framework analysis relating to Responsible AI, both with an in-depth as well as a comparative dimension.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you are interested, please send a brief expression of interest including a tentative title, author list, and abstract to Dr. Marcelo Milrad at marcelo.milrad@lnu.se.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The journal's submission platform (Editorial Manager®) will be available for the invited authors for submitting submissions to this Special Issue. Please refer to the Guide for Authors to prepare the manuscript and select the article type “VSI: Responsible AI in Education" when submitting your manuscript online. Both the Guide for Authors and the submission portal can be found on the journal Homepage here: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/journals/computers-and-education-artificial-intelligence/2666-920X/guide-for-authors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/journals/computers-and-education-artificial-intelligence/2666-920X/guide-for-authors&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Call announced  - February 2023&lt;br&gt;Full paper submitted - August 30th, 2023&lt;br&gt;Paper reviewed - November 30th 2023&lt;br&gt;Final submission - February 1st, 2024&lt;br&gt;Publication - March 2024&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All submissions deemed suitable to be sent for peer review will be reviewed by at least two independent reviewers. Once your manuscript is accepted, it will go into production, and will be simultaneously published in the current regular issue and pulled into the online Special Issue. Articles from this Special Issue will appear in different regular issues of the journal, though they will be clearly marked and branded as Special Issue articles.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here is an example: &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/science-of-the-total-environment/special-issue/10SWS2W7VVV"&gt;https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/science-of-the-total-environment/special-issue/10SWS2W7VVV&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What is a VSI (Virtual Special Issue):&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Upon its editorial acceptance, articles submitted to a VSI will go into production immediately. It will be published in the latest regular issue while simultaneously being presented on the Special Issue webpage. The regular issues will mark and brand the Special Issue articles.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;References:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;McGrath, C., Pargman, T. C., Juth, N., &amp; Palmgren, P. J. (2023). University teachers' perceptions of responsibility and artificial intelligence in higher education-An experimental philosophical study. Computers and Education: Artificial Intelligence, 100139.&lt;/p&gt;
