&lt;p&gt;A smart city refers to a city that, as a result of a basic infrastructure, can provide all its citizens with a good quality of life, inserted in the context of a sustainable environment through the use of smart technological solutions. The current challenges faced by a smart city are observed in different domains: from mobility to health, through energy, infrastructure, security, among many others. To fulfill the premise of improving the quality of life and smart outcomes for citizens, a “people-centric” paradigm becomes essential with strategic technology components to support it. Although there are countless efforts and contributions in this regard, it is clear that there is still a large space for research in this area. The proliferation of digital transformation and the exponential advance that has taken place in technological areas, associated with the pandemic that is still felt today, brought the need to explore the benefits of emerging areas and brought even greater importance to the collection, analysis, processing and sharing of data, its application to different domains and raised questions related to security and privacy. All this with the aim of building more resilient cities, flexible to change and with a focus on sustainable growth and for the benefit of the citizens. These advances will be made possible through technological research, supporting infrastructure and their application in real scenarios and complex systems.&lt;/p&gt;
