&lt;p&gt;This Special Issue focuses on future cities and in particular, the people who live in them, the natural environment they must coexist with; and the technologies that will facilitate human activities without causing irreversible damage to the environment. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It is believed that understanding the people-environment-infrastructure relationships is the key to make future cities and society resilient and sustainable. Infrastructure includes basic facilities that are place-based and are serving public interests and supporting a great variety of economic activities. Many infrastructure systems also have a high capital-output ratio and a long lifespan. Therefore, there is an urgent need to develop fundamentally new ways of planning and constructing infrastructure for future cities and conceiving the ways in which infrastructure will interact with people and the environment in future cities. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This Special Issue welcomes innovative and interdisciplinary contributions that focus on the people-environment-infrastructure relationship in future cities. &lt;/p&gt;
