&lt;p&gt;Sustainable Cities and Society&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
	Energy storage systems (ESSs) are emerging as a solution to improve efficiency, sustainability, and reliability of energy systems. ESSs could foster the integration of renewable energy technologies, such as wind and solar, by accommodating their intermittent nature. In addition, energy storage can serve as a buffer both for energy carriers (such as grids and pipelines) and remote (off-grid) communities, to enhance their resiliency in case of extreme circumstances such as natural hazards or operational disruptions. In the light of the above emergence of ESSs, their integration to balance the demand and supply sides of energy systems still remains a challenge and a complex task, due to multiplicity of the involved decision variables, fluctuating nature of energy demand, uncertainties on the supply side, and variability of technologies, cost and scale. These complexities have given rise to the adoption of artificial intelligence (AI) and smart tools founded on the increasing use of data collection and analysis, as well as smart technologies based on recent advancements in hardware and software for digitization and visualization, in order to intelligently control and operate energy storage systems integrated at building, district, and community scales. The special issue welcomes technical papers, case studies, and state-of-the-art reviews on use of smart tools and technologies in design, integration, operation, and control of ESSs that include (but not limited to):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- Data-driven algorithms for optimization of ESSs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- Applications of artificial intelligence in operation and control of ESSs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- Economics of intelligent energy storage&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- Real-time and model predictive controls for ESSs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- Smart scheduling for ESSs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- Networked/distributed ESSs and intelligent coordination&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- Smart design and automation for ESSs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- Data-driven reliability and resiliency assessment of ESSs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- Digitization and building information modeling for ESSs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	- IoT and cloud systems for ESSs monitoring and control&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;Timeline and submission instructions:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Deadline for Submissions: November 1, 2021&lt;/p&gt;
