&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Emerging markets are currently undergoing economic, social, political and demographic transitions. They can leverage digital technologies to drive business innovation (Dana et al., 2022). There is growth in the development of innovative ideas and products by local companies in emerging countries (Zeschky et al., 2011). Thus, the role of business groups is fundamental in emerging economies (Khanna &amp; Rivkin, 2001). The strategies of small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) have been influenced by the challenges posed by digital technologies (Ferreira et al., 2022). Because of the varying characteristics of emerging economies, analysis of the adoption of ICTs at the micro, meso and macro levels is essential (Tortorella et al., 2021). There are differences not only between advanced and emerging countries but also between different emerging markets (Claessens &amp; Yurtoglu, 2013). The institutional perspective is useful for companies in emerging economies to improve their competitiveness, especially when growing internationally (Peng et al., 2008).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Authors such as Tamvada et al. (2022) have called for the validation and prioritization of research into the risks of SMEs’ implementation of Industry 4.0 in emerging economies, highlighting the lack of literature. Thus, expanding the lines of research in this field and extending the scientific study of the impact of digitalization in emerging countries is important. A formal call is made to the academic research community to contribute to these research lines. Scholars are invited to consider the questions raised and to consider others that they deem relevant within this thematic framework. Such collaboration will be valuable for advancing knowledge in this field and for benefiting society as a whole. Other issues that could also be considered in this Special Issue include the following:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How does the implementation of digital technologies in developing economies facilitate the spread of innovative practices in the corporate world?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;What are the present economic and social consequences of digitalization in developing economies?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;What are the challenges and opportunities associated with the deployment of digital technologies in emerging markets?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How do digital technologies affect the innovation potential of firms?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can companies take advantage of the new opportunities offered by digital technologies to innovate and thrive in emerging countries?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special Issue workshop:&lt;/strong&gt; There are plans to run a paper development workshop for this Special Issue during the IMIP Conference in Hangzhou (China) between 13 Oct and 15 Oct 2023. Participants of the workshop are encouraged to submit their full papers via the conference submission system. The Special Issue Guest Editors will then invite authors of a selection of papers to this workshop to discuss their papers. All submissions to the Special Issue will then be administered under the journal’s review process.&lt;/p&gt;
