&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1.Proposed SI title: Bridging the gap between adoption theory and practice in technological forecasting&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2.Short title: &lt;/strong&gt;Theory_forecasting&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. Contact details guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jaime Bonnín Roca&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;a href="mailto:j.bonnin.roca@tue.nl"&gt;j.bonnin.roca@tue.nl&lt;/a&gt; ORCID 0000-0003-4244-0357&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Elena M. Tur&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;a href="mailto:e.m.mas.tur@tue.nl"&gt;e.m.mas.tur@tue.nl&lt;/a&gt; ORCID 0000-0001-9634-0090&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Georgios Papachristos, &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;a href="mailto:g.papachristos@tue.nl"&gt;g.papachristos@tue.nl&lt;/a&gt;&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;ORCID 0000-0001-7622-3364&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All guest editors have the same affiliation:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Eindhoven University of Technology, Department of Industrial Engineering &amp; Innovation Sciences; P.O. Box 513, 5600, MB, Eindhoven, The Netherlands&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Assigned editor at &lt;em&gt;Technological Forecasting and Social Change&lt;/em&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Scott Cunningham, &lt;a href="mailto:scott.cunningham@strath.ac.uk"&gt;scott.cunningham@strath.ac.uk&lt;/a&gt; ORCID 0000-0001-7140-916X&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;University of Strathclyde, School of Government and Public Policy, Glasgow, United Kingdom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. Scope&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The main purpose of this Special Issue is to provide stronger theoretical foundations to the field of technological forecasting. The overarching research question are:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can innovation theories explain empirical results from forecasting studies?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can the practice of forecasting improve by incorporating insights from existing innovation theories?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In particular, this Special Issue focuses on empirical forecasting methods aimed at predicting &lt;strong&gt;technology adoption and diffusion&lt;/strong&gt;. These include technometrics and judgemental methods, among others, which may include structural and predictive variables in addition to time. This Special Issue does &lt;strong&gt;not&lt;/strong&gt; focus on naïve forecasting methods, or on forecasting methods targeted at financial forecasting.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. Relevance&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our ultimate goal is to increase rigor in the field of technological forecasting. The academic standards for reliability and validity of science are higher than ever. At the same time, we observe a large number of publications in the journal which propose new forecasting tools and methods with little theoretical background, and limited generalizability.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;6. Necessity&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Theory-oriented researchers usually have a different background, and publish in different journals, than practice-oriented researchers. If nothing is done, the gap between one and the other will continue widening. We see this Special Issue as an opportunity to reconcile both worlds.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;7. Promotion&lt;/strong&gt;: this SI will attract quality submissions by holding a paper development workshop (see below), and by exploiting the network of the guest editors. We are also considering the option of hosting a session at one academic conference.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;8. Management&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first step of the review process will be to decide whether a submitted paper is relevant to the Special Issue, and meets the standards of academic research, or should be desk rejected. For this first step, submitted papers will be distributed evenly among the team of guest editors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once we have filtered the papers which are not relevant, the guest editors will gather to discuss the remaining papers. After the discussion, each paper will be assigned to one of the guest editors, always trying to match the topic of the paper and the expertise of the guest editor.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Given that the purpose of the SI is to bridge the gap between theory and practice, we think it is essential to have at least one referee who is an expert in the theory with which the authors substantiate their work, and one referee who is an expert in the forecasting method they use. To mitigate the risk of referees not accepting our invitation, or not delivering their reviews on time, we will initially send request to four referees (two on the theoretical side, and two on the empirical side).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The referees will ideally be drawn from the list of references of the paper, and the personal network of the guest editors. If this were not enough, or the selected referees were not responsive, we would use the journal’s database to find additional referees.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The guest editor will also review the paper and provide additional feedback to the authors not covered by the referees, if deemed necessary. This feedback might be important, for instance, to increase the consistency between papers in the SI.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Papers with mixed reviews will be discussed by the whole team of guest editors, before making the final decision.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;9. Call for papers&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This Special Issue focuses on empirical forecasting methods aimed at predicting technology adoption and diffusion. These include technometrics (Coccia, 2005) and judgemental methods, among others, which may include structural and predictive variables in addition to time. This Special Issue does &lt;strong&gt;not&lt;/strong&gt; focus on naïve forecasting methods, or on forecasting methods targeted at financial forecasting.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The field of technological forecasting was born in, and has always inherently been connected to, practice. Early forecasting practice during the Cold War was driven by government initiatives to develop comprehensive R&amp;D strategies for technological and military supremacy (Coates et al., 2001). These initiatives resulted in techniques such as TRIZ (Altshuller and Shapiro, 1956), Delphi (RAND, 1967), and basic trend and envelope analyses (Schon, 1967). During these early stages, knowledge exchange was difficult due to the small size of forecasting communities, and the sensitive nature of the topics tackled. As forecasting methods became more popular, large corporations became some of the most important locus of forecasting research, adapting existing methods and creating their own. For instance, companies such as Motorola, BP, or Philips were instrumental in developing technology roadmapping tools (Kerr and Phaal, 2020) which now are widely used by companies, governments, and research institutions internationally.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Nowadays, the forecasting community has grown substantially and is international (Sarin et al., 2020). As a result, its research output has increased exponentially. That said, the application of forecasting tools differs across communities, and today one may come across with different &lt;em&gt;schools of thought&lt;/em&gt; (Park et al., 2020). In principle, this increased diversity in the research community is positive for enhancing creativity and promoting scientific developments. However, some scholars point out a risk for forecasting tools, as their adoption increases by the different communities, the rigor in their implementation may decrease (Durance and Godet, 2010; Hasson and Keeney, 2011; Morgan, 2014).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Parallel to developments in technological forecasting methods, scholars in other fields related to innovation have produced theories which have greatly increased our understanding of how technology is developed and commercialized. Among other advancements, recent developments in innovation systems (Markard, 2020) and the multi-level perspective (Geels et al., 2017) hold, in principle, more explanatory power than older linear models based on technology-push and market-pull forces. Economic geographers have worked extensively on industrial clusters (Buenstorf and Costa, 2018) and economic complexity (Hidalgo, 2021) theories which may be used to predict patterns of regional growth and technological specialization. Sociologists and psychologists have deepened our understanding of how individual preferences, combined with environmental factors, affect technology adoption and diffusion (Bonnin Roca and O’Sullivan, 2020; Penttilä et al., 2020).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Despite these theoretical advances, much of the forecasting literature remains close to its roots and focuses only on the development of ad-hoc methods, without providing a proper theoretical substantiation of their methodological choices or of their observed results. This limits the generalizability of forecasting research, and lowers the validity and reliability of a large portion of the body of work. In other words, it is challenging to assess &lt;em&gt;why&lt;/em&gt; a certain method or model works (or not), and &lt;em&gt;how&lt;/em&gt; to assess ex-ante the quality of a forecast, beyond common statistical measures. These problems might be exacerbated in the future with the use of forecasting methods based on the use of artificial intelligence (AI) such as deep learning (Shrestha et al., 2021) or neural networks (Liébana-Cabanillas et al., 2018), which suffer from the ‘black box’ (Castelvecchi, 2016) problem of not being able to offer a transparent explanation of how they work.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This Special Issue aims to increase the rigor in forecasting practice, by enhancing the theoretical substantiation of the most commonly used forecasting techniques. Areas of interest include, but are not limited to:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The development of theoretically-backed arguments for the selection of forecasting models, including scientometrics&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Interdisciplinary work aimed at reconciling results from forecasting practice with results from other disciplines&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Provision of theoretical underpinnings to the different sources of uncertainty in a forecast, and their expected evolution in time&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Development of theoretical criteria to assess, ex-ante, the quality of a forecast&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Creation of generalizable guidelines for data cleaning and processing, based on theoretical grounds&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Work devoted to the harmonisation of forecasting practices across different communities of researchers and practitioners&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Studies related to the individual, organizational, and cultural factors to take into account when conducting judgmental methods, and their expected effect on forecast accuracy&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The revision of forecasts already published in the literature to explain why they were successful (or failed), based on existing theory&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Papers in this Special Issue may use both qualitative and quantitative research methods. In any case, papers are expected to have a solid theoretical foundation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special Issue workshop&lt;/strong&gt;: We plan to organize a hybrid, one-day development workshop for the special issue at Eindhoven University of Technology, on November 27&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt;, 2023. Authors interested in participating are encouraged to send their extended abstracts to the guest editors. Word limit for extended abstracts is 1000 words, excluding references. Guest editors will then invite authors of a selection of papers to this workshop to discuss their papers, although all submissions to the SI need to go through the journal’s review process later.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please direct questions about the submission process, or any administrative matter, to the guest editors. Questions about expectations, requirements, and the appropriateness of a topic should be directed to the guest editors of the special issue.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All the submissions should follow the general author guidelines of Technological Forecasting &amp; Social Change available at&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/journals/technological-forecasting-and-social-change/0040-1625/guide-for-authors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/journals/technological-forecasting-and-social-change/0040-1625/guide-for-authors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Full-length papers should be submitted through the journal’s online submission system before June 2&lt;sup&gt;nd&lt;/sup&gt;, 2024. Please make sure to tick the box “Special Issue: &lt;strong&gt;Theory_forecasting&lt;/strong&gt;” when submit and indicate in your cover letter that the submission is intended for this Special Issue.&lt;/p&gt;
