&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Background and Context&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The development of the Internet in recent decades has prompted firms to adapt their business models to a new data-driven era (Ribeiro-Navarrete et al., 2021). A multitude of digital strategies and techniques have been developed in which the development of new opportunities for data-driven decision-making is sought (Janssen et al., 2017). At the same time, in a digital ecosystem in which technology is growing exponentially, the adoption of emerging technologies has positioned itself as a fundamental element for creating value in companies (Jin and Li, 2012; Saura et al., 2022).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The adoption and use of emerging data-driven technologies drive the global strategies of firms as well as increase the value of their products and services (Lages, 2016). Data-driven technologies such as artificial intelligence (AI), Big Data, Machine Learning, Internet of Things (IoT) or new digital tools used in the industry 4.0, are configured as an optimal option for firms seeking to develop strategies adapted to a new connected era (Zhu et al., 2004; Bai et al., 2020). In the current operating environment, it is also critical to evaluate how the use of such technologies can help businesses cope with the recessionary pressures and tightening monetary regimes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this paradigm, in which companies begin to adopt emerging technologies to improve their business models, sustainability has become one of the most considered variables in the scientific literature in recent years (Stuermer et al., 2017). Sustainability allows firms not only to adopt new forms of development and sustainable production, but also optimizes any action that the firm develops with the aim of being profitable and respecting the environment (Whelan and Fink, 2016). In an ecosystem in which emerging technologies and their applications are essential for business growth, sustainability is a variable that must be considered to boost innovation. There are many studies that focus on analyzing the adoption and emerging technologies as well as sustainable strategies in companies, however, from a scientific point of view, the linking of both concepts allows us to understand these relevant issues from a new digital landscape (Khan et al., 2021).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Therefore, this Special Issue aims to cover this field of research by evaluating theoretical or practical contributions, mixed approaches, reviews, empirical or qualitative studies. For this Special Issue, we invite paper contributions related to any of the topics outlined above and which clearly relate to emerging technologies applications in a data-drive era of sustainability across various verticals of business (marketing, finance, supply chain, operations etc).&lt;/p&gt;
