&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short title (VSI): AI&amp;SD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest Editors&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Marta F. Arroyabe &lt;/strong&gt;(&lt;a href="mailto:mf17255@essex.ac.uk"&gt;mf17255@essex.ac.uk&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;br&gt;Essex Business School, University of Essex, UK&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Martin H Kunc &lt;/strong&gt;(&lt;a href="mailto:M.H.Kunc@soton.ac.uk"&gt;M.H.Kunc@soton.ac.uk&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;br&gt;Southampton Business School, University of Southampton, UK&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Nieves Arranz&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;a href="mailto:narranz@cee.uned.es"&gt;narranz@cee.uned.es&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;br&gt;Faculty of Business and Economics, UNED, Spain&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Juan Carlos Fernandez de Arroyabe &lt;/strong&gt;(&lt;a href="mailto:jcfern@essex.ac.uk"&gt;jcfern@essex.ac.uk&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;br&gt;Essex Business School, University of Essex, UK&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Martin Schumann&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;a href="mailto:m.schumann@maastrichtuniversity.nl"&gt;m.schumann@maastrichtuniversity.nl&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;br&gt;School of Business and Economics, Maastricht University, NL&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Call for Papers&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We invite papers to be considered for a Special Issue&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;to explore novel analyses and approaches to the forecast of &lt;strong&gt;technological systems development&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;considering (but not limited to) Artificial Intelligence and System Dynamics methodologies.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The importance of the Systems Dynamics perspective (SD) has been highlighted by a wide variety of areas, including complex ecological, economic, and business systems (Walters et al., 2016; Zhao et al., 2018; Bahaddin et al., 2019; Kapmeier et al., 2021), permitting the simulation of dynamically complex problems (Sterman, 2000). System dynamics theory considers that complex systems are composed of elements, parts, or subsystems, whose interaction lead to diverse system evolutionary paths (Bergek, 2019; Russell and Smorodinskaya, 2018; Zhao et al., 2018; Walters et al., 2016; Bergek et al., 2008; Sterman, 2001). Zhao et al. (2018) and Sterman (2000) conclude that effective understanding of technological systems, in a world of growing dynamic complexity, requires us to become systems thinkers-to expand the boundaries of our mental models and develop tools to understand how the structure of complex systems creates their patterns. System Dynamics has a strong tradition on forecasting and evaluation the evolution of social systems, such as tourism (Torres et al, 2021), healthcare workforce (Willis et al, 2018), either alone or combined with scenarios (Kunc and O’Brien, 2017).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Artificial intelligence (AI), and more specifically machine learning (ML) has grown significantly in the last years. Arranz et al. (2021), Huo and Chaudhry (2021), Gruetzemacher et al. (2021), Salminen et al. (2019) and Minbashian et al. (2010) have pointed out that applying Machine Learning (ML) techniques allow addressing complex modelling with a high level of accuracy. First, the application of artificial neural networks (ANNs), for example, permits determining all interactions, using learning algorithms. Second, technological systems and forecasting problems usually involve a large amount of data and many variables (Russell et al., 2018), making machine learning the best approach. Last, machine learning responds to situations where there is a lack of data, or in a variety of formats, or the lack of definition of relationship models between variables. Therefore, these techniques will allow researchers to solve previous limitations of classical statistical models, providing a higher level of explanatory variance, which will result in a better understanding and quantification of how various input variables affect the development of technological systems, forecasting, and dynamics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this context, Zhao et al. (2018), Sterman et al. (2015), Liu et al. (2015), Gruetzemacher et al. (2021) and Mendoza et al. (2014) have highlighted the importance of approaching technological processes and decisions from a broader perspective, considering their complexity and evolution. While, SD models provide a high-level understanding of the processes and aid in designing policies to achieve specific system behaviours, AI, and particularly ML techniques benefit the modelling process by saving on resources, improving the potential to provide insights into the system and preventing subjectivity of the modeller (Shrestha et al., 2021; Garbero et al., 2021; Jana et al., 2021; Gruetzemacher et al., 2021). Therefore, a combination of SD with AI will lead to addressing technological systems, forecasting and planning with greater accuracy and robustness.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This special issue intends to publish research that combines systems dynamics and artificial intelligence in its application to forecasting of technological systems. We welcome research leading to empirical papers (e.g. case studies, experiments, surveys, models) and theoretical (e.g. conceptual or literature review). First, the special issue prioritizes the empirical papers, which combine SD with ML methods, developing qualitative and quantitative analysis. This combination will facilitate not only to address the classic problems of process simulation, but also to address other typical aspects of technological systems, where feedback causality, or complex nonlinear dynamics, complementarities, substitution effects, characterization of the effect of policies, are key drivers of their evolution and difficult to forecast. Second, the special issue also admits conceptual papers and reviews, prioritizing those that use combining SD with machine learning techniques (for example, natural language and polarity analysis). Finally, the scope of the special issue is opened to a wide spectrum of areas and sectors, such as environmental problems, innovation systems, smart supply chain models, technological startup processes, and transportation systems, among others. We address the following non-exhaustive list of research questions:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can Systems Dynamics and AI simulations be employed for forecasting complex problems?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can Systems Dynamics and AI simulations provide an understanding of innovation and eco-innovation systems?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can Systems Dynamics and AI simulations be employed to assess collaborative innovation impact on the innovation systems?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can Systems Dynamics and AI simulations help in the understanding of technological problems?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can Systems Dynamics and AI simulations be applied to the planning of technological systems?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;How can Systems Dynamics and AI simulations be applied to the analysis of technology impacts in the environmental systems?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thus, we aim that the collection of papers in this special issue will help the ongoing dialogue among scholars from a diverse set of disciplines that share an interest in the application de Systems Dynamics and AI to forecasting and planning processes. We also hope that the special issue will help develop a unified body of knowledge on the topic. In addition, we hope this special issue will offer decision and policy-makers some guidance to assess the conditions under which the use of AI can add value to managers and policy-makers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Submission process&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Technological Forecasting Social Changes publishes articles of a multi-disciplinary and interdisciplinary nature as well as empirical research from within traditional disciplines and managerial functions. With contributions from around the globe, the Journal includes articles across the full range of business and management disciplines.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is an open call and will be widely advertised across the several networks the Guest editors belong to. The Guest Editors will first screen the papers and will desk-reject the papers that do not fit with the call for papers. The remaining papers will be regularly refereed by three reviewers according to the usual standards of the Journal. The Guest editors will review the report and make a proposal of the accepted papers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;High-quality papers that do not make the final set of papers for the special issue may be considered for publication in a regular issue of the journal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For more information, please contact &lt;strong&gt;Marta F. Arroyabe&lt;/strong&gt;, Essex Business School, University of Essex, UK, &lt;a href="mailto:mf17255@essex.ac.uk"&gt;mf17255@essex.ac.uk&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
