&lt;p&gt;In intelligent decision making, a decision maker must decide on what actions to execute in order to achieve goals in an environment. A decision maker (or an agent) can be artificial intelligence (AI) or a human. In recent years, significant improvements in neural networks and machine learning have spurred the usage of AI in many real-world decision-making problems, such as autonomous driving, gaming, and border testing against pandemics. The outcomes of these problems can depend on the decisions of a single agent, or the joint decisions of two or more agents. The former is traditional single-agent decision making, while the latter is the increasingly popular multi-agent decision-making setting.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Game theory provides a mathematical framework to model strategic interactions among multiple agents. The modern study of multi-agent decision making, thereby, often combines game theory, machine learning and neural networks. Neural networks empower decision making with efficient representation learning. On the other hand, game theory lays theoretical underpinnings and sheds light on the outcomes of multi-agent decision making.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The goal of this special issue is to promote collaboration and the cross-fertilization of ideas between researchers working from different aspects of game theory, intelligent decision making, machine learning and neural networks. We welcome both original theory- and application-driven contributions to this field, and we particularly encourage work in machine learning and neural networks for multi-agent decision making.&lt;/p&gt;
