&lt;p&gt;This special issue of Computers in Biology and Medicine journal focuses on discussing, based both on review and research papers, the role, specific applications, advantages, and disadvantages of explainable versus non-explainable features in biomedical speech and voice analysis.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Essentially, papers should focus on handcrafted procedures, representing the former type of features, in &lt;br&gt;contrast with learned ones, representing the latter type. Additionally, the possibility of having explainable learned features for particular applications is also of great interest for this special issue. Particular applications include, but are not limited to: vocal and nasal tracts pathology detection; vocal folds pathology detection; lungs pathology detection; heart pathology detection based on speech and voice analysis; depression detection based on speech and voice analysis; neurodegenerative diseases early detection, such as Parkinson, Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS), Multiple Sclerosis (MS), and so on, based on speech and voice analysis; voice synthesis and conversion to enhance affected speech signals from impaired people; among others.&lt;/p&gt;
