&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Aims&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt; of the Special Issue&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Advanced technologies such as Artificial intelligence, Big Data, 5G, Internet of Things, Cloud, Cyber-Physical Systems, and Digital Twins are empowering the emergence of smart manufacturing systems. A smart wafer fabrication facility facilitates transparent manufacturing platform by integrating technological advances in computer networks, data integration, and telecommunication to enable modeling, analytics and intelligence for smart production. On the other hand, leading nations have reemphasized the importance of domestic semiconductor manufacturing for supply chain resilience. Meanwhile, the pros and cons of wafer fabs regarding sustainability and circular economy for semiconductor manufacturing are not fully investigated in the restructuring global semiconductor manufacturing supply chains, while new technologies and intelligent solutions are needed for cleaner production.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thus, this special issue of the &lt;em&gt;Computers &amp; Industrial Engineering&lt;/em&gt; (&lt;strong&gt;C&amp;IE&lt;/strong&gt;) aims to address emergent research issues involved on recent developments of intelligent manufacturing and circular economy for semiconductor manufacturing. Semiconductor manufacturing is capital intensive and very complex due to tightly constrained lengthy production processes, reentrant process flows, sophisticated equipment, volatile demands, and complicated product mix. While big data is accumulated due to the fully automated semiconductor manufacturing facilities and logistics systems for business integration, by combining equipment automation with decision technologies and exploiting useful rules and patterns from data, potential failures during the early stages can be anticipated for real-time decisions. Indeed, the intelligence and real-time decision-making capabilities of equipment coupled with the system-level fabrication automation in advanced fabs have changed the paradigm of future semiconductor manufacturing. In addition to shop-floor control concerns, supply chain management problems have become more and more important which necessitate a horizontal integration of the semiconductor supply chain and digital transformation for the industry ecosystem.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Scope&lt;strong&gt; of the Special Issue&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This special issue welcomes contributions that may concern to recent advances and future perspectives describing various research areas, novel approaches, and important issues in different regions to address the needs for intelligent manufacturing and circular economy for semiconductor manufacturing. Special attentions will be paid to papers focusing on smart manufacturing and cleaner production via intelligent technologies to enhance sustainability, including the following topics and related issues:&lt;/p&gt;
