&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SI closes for submissions&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;strong&gt;30 June, 2023&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SI finished&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;strong&gt;31&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt; March, 2024&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Approximation publication date: &lt;/strong&gt;on-line first upon acceptance&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Effective waste management strategies have a vital role in addressing the hazardous impacts on the environment. In waste management, analytical approaches can be used effectively to inspect possible trade-offs among alternatives, which can help in choosing appropriate decision-making schemes. Multi-Criteria Decision-Making (MCDM) has been widely used as a novel approach in the decision-making process. MCDM allows researchers to evaluate different choices with restricted resources and within a limited time. The main goal of this Special Issue is to present the readers with a group of research studies that focus on the deployment of the MCDM tools for waste management.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dr. Mehrbakhsh Nilashi, UCSI University, &lt;a href="mailto:nilashidotnet@hotmail.com;"&gt;nilashidotnet@hotmail.com;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dr. Mohammad Iranmanesh, Edith Cowan University, &lt;a href="mailto:m.iranmanesh@ecu.edu.au;"&gt;m.iranmanesh@ecu.edu.au;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dr. Morteza Ghobakhloo, Kaunas University of Technology, &lt;a href="mailto:morteza.ghobakhloo@ktu.lt;"&gt;morteza.ghobakhloo@ktu.lt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dr. Rabab Ali Abumalloh, Imam Abdulrahman Bin Faisal University, &lt;a href="mailto:ramolloh@iau.edu.sa"&gt;ramolloh@iau.edu.sa&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Wastes are created by individuals in almost all environments in different forms including liquids, gases, and solids. Wastes can be categorized, based on the source, into construction and mining, agricultural, commercial, industrial, domestic, and medical waste. Because of the variations in the deployed strategy of operation and management, each source produces a different amount of waste. For example, in the construction field, the amount of generated waste is growing in a fast manner, accounting for 35% of the overall global waste. Wastes produced from construction lead to detrimental impacts on the environment and cause huge financial losses. Industrial waste, on the other hand, entails hazardous and toxic materials that impact the health of community members. Medical waste might include several types, such as sharp materials, blood, parts of the human body, chemical materials, pharmaceutical materials, infectious materials, and health-related devices. Effective waste management strategies have a vital role in compacting the hazards associated with waste. In waste management, analytical approaches can be used effectively to inspect possible trade-offs among alternatives, which can help choose appropriate planning, operation, and decision-making schemes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In real life, decision-making is usually a complex procedure that needs a suitable and dependable guide. In previous literature, several statistical and non-statistical approaches have been deployed for facilitating the decision-making process in complex situations. Still, the decision-making process by individuals is subject to several shortcomings in terms of prediction reliability and accuracy. Real-world decisions usually entail many-sided or multi-attribute tasks that should be performed by selecting one of the available choices within specific conditions. On the contrary to single-sided tasks, multi-attribute tasks conform to several choices with trade-offs among those choices. Multi-Criteria Decision-Making (MCDM) is an efficient quantitative approach used effectively to help decision-makers reach the right choice and solve problems with many alternatives and several conditions. MCDM has been significantly extended beyond traditional approaches, providing insightful and informal procedures in the decision-making process. MCDM allows researchers to evaluate different choices with restricted resources and within a limited time. MCDM can be used to investigate several economic, environmental, and social dimensions in waste management and handle potential conflicts to provide a solution in an optimized manner. Unlike conventional MCDM approaches, fuzzy decision-making presents suitable approaches to handle ambiguities and uncertainties. The fuzzy set theory focuses on handling issues related to subjective, ambiguous, and imprecise decisions. It can measure the linguistic aspects of possible choices and alternatives to allow individual or group decision-making. The fuzzy set theory has been extended and deployed in several fields of research, entailing interval-valued fuzzy sets, intuitionistic fuzzy sets, interval-valued intuitionistic fuzzy sets, rough sets, grey sets, bipolar fuzzy sets, hesitant fuzzy sets, fuzzy oriented sets, and fuzzy numbers. Recently, the fuzzy sets method has seen substantial development theoretically and practically. Hence, along with traditional MCDM techniques, this Special Issue invites studies that deploy the fuzzy theory, such as rough sets, fuzzy sets, neutrosophic sets in waste management. This Special Issue aims to provide new research articles on multi-criteria decisions in a multidisciplinary environment, focusing on waste management.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The main goal of this Special Issue is to present the readers with a group of research studies that focus on the deployment of the MCDM tools for waste management. The management of possible threats that are linked to waste is also a topic of interest in this Special Issue. The domain of this Special Issue entails the deployment of emerging developments in discrete and continuous MCDM approaches to waste management. As editors, we welcome the studies that present state-of-the-art multi-criteria decision-making by utilizing the fuzzy environment to threats and risks related to the practical implementation of waste management. We welcome high-quality research articles related to the design, integration, deployment of multi-criteria decisions in waste management and operation. Scholars are welcome to submit research studies that investigate issues of multi-objective modeling of decision-making in waste management to present state-of-the-art sustainable solutions. Both empirical and review studies that can provide in-depth perceptions about the deployment of MCDM tools in waste management are welcome. The proposed research studies should provide novel MCDM systems to address waste, particularly in the following directions of research:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;MCDM modeling for waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Group decision making of waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;MCDM applications for waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Decision making for sustainable management of waste&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Discrete and continuous MCDM approaches for waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Decision support systems for waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Fuzzy MCDM application for waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Methods for MCDM in waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;MCDM in strategic waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Risk evaluation in waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;MCDM soft-computing approaches for waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Survey studies in MCDM approach for waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The multi-objective problem in waste management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The application of MCDM tools to address the increase of waste during the COVID-19 crisis&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Paper submissions for the special issue should follow the submission format and guidelines for regular papers and be submitted at https://ees.elsevier.com/asoc. Papers that either lack originality, clarity in presentation, or fall outside the scope of the special issue will be desk-rejected without further review. Authors should select “VSI:Waste Manage MCDM” when they reach the “Article Type” step in the submission process. The submitted papers must propose original research that has not been published nor is currently under review in other venues.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;IMPORTANT DATES&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Submission deadline: May 31, 2023&lt;br&gt;Final acceptance notification to authors: October 30, 2023&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With the pandemic devastation caused by the nCoV-2 virus affecting almost all the countries globally leading to innumerable casualties and inflicting inconvenience to the normal socio-economic order, need for timely, non-invasive and low cost testing and diagnosis techniques has become inevitable. The conventional techniques employed for diagnosis of infectious diseases are found to be unable rise up to the cause due to the inherent uncertainties associated with the nature of the virus causing infections.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Computational Intelligence and Soft Computing, a symbiosis of several intelligent tools and techniques is often being used to address the uncertainties and imprecision prevalent in the real world. The underlying tools are intelligent enough to analyze and process real world data to extract meaningful and relevant information.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As such, a plethora of initiatives is being explored to involve computational intelligence and allied techniques address the current impasse. The proposed techniques are mainly focused on using suitable intelligent algorithms and innovations to decipher the presence of the disease causing virus by resorting to proper modelling, early prediction and detection from data collected from infected (both symptomatic and non-symptomatic) and non-infected subjects, but also to study and prevail the expected impacts on society on long-termed lockdowns and industrial production standstills.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;"Applied Soft Computing" wants to respond on those pressing issues and offer a special avenue for publications with strong relation to COVID-19. Effectively starting June 1, there is a Fast Track submission option available at our journal. It will stay open until further notice.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Those Fast Track submissions will be handled by selected editors from ASOC Editorial Board in an expedited procedure. It means: at most one revision round (however, submissions rejected for such reason can still be resubmitted as regular submissions), and an envisaged processing time of at most 3 months. Submissions accepted for publication will appear in a regular volume, in a related Article Collection in ScienceDirect area of ASOC, and in Elsevier's Covid-19 Repository.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To submit to the Fast Track, prepare it as a regular submission, but select the Article Type "FT: Covid-19". Note that submissions under this Article Type with no or minor relation to above themes will be rejected straight-away. Also we can make this offer only for one submission per research group or leading author, for fairness to other authors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Otherwise, general submission standards apply. Topics include but are not limited to the following:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Intelligent Modelling of Pandemics&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Analysis of spreads and outbreaks&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Intelligent Data Analysis Tools for Pandemics&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Early Detection and Prediction Mechanisms&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Optimization of Health Care Resources and Health Care Informatics&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Intelligent multi sensing methods for automatic symptoms analysis&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Intelligent Diagnosis and Prognosis Mechanisms &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Intelligent Modes of Health Care Measures&lt;br&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Non-invasive Testing and Treatment Provisions&lt;br&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Intelligent Models for Social Distancing and Social Interaction&lt;br&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Contact-less Human Etiquette&lt;br&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Social influence analysis&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
